# Project Rules — DwayneLocke.com

## What this site is
A thesis/publication home for Dwayne Locke. Essays lead. The business-dependency
assessment is a secondary tool, never the headline. The site reads like a calm
publication, not a SaaS landing page or a sales funnel.

## Voice (non-negotiable)
- Observational and grounded, not authoritative. The stance is "an operator working
  through this in the open," NOT "an expert with all the answers."
- Speak to the reader as "you." Dwayne refers to himself as "I." Never "we" as if the
  reader and author are one.
- No hype. No "revolutionize / transform / unlock / supercharge." No guru or coach tone.
- No fabricated proof. Never invent statistics, testimonials, client names, logos, or
  benchmark numbers. If proof doesn't exist yet, leave it out — do not manufacture it.
- AI/automation is named openly in essays (the content is about it), but the site never
  leads with AI as a pitch. Lead with the observation, not the technology.
- Findings in the assessment are stated as observation ("X appears to create the most
  dependency"), hedged, never as verdicts.

## Design tokens
Defined once in src/styles/global.css. Do not hardcode hex values elsewhere.
  --ink: #1c1a17;        /* primary text */
  --ink-soft: #4a463f;   /* secondary text */
  --ink-faint: #807a70;  /* tertiary / captions */
  --paper: #f4f1ea;      /* page background */
  --paper-2: #ece7dc;    /* alt background, dark sections invert */
  --card: #fbf9f4;       /* card background */
  --accent: #b8552f;     /* rust accent */
  --accent-soft: #d8a48c;
  --accent-bg: #f3e3da;
  --line: rgba(28,26,23,0.12);
Fonts:
  Display/serif: 'Fraunces' (headings, essay titles, pull-quotes — use italics for emphasis)
  Body/sans: 'Outfit' (UI, body, nav)
Feel: warm paper, editorial, generous whitespace, calm. Reading width ~720px for essays.
No loud gradients, no purple, no stock-startup look.

## Structure rules
- Essays are Markdown files in src/content/essays/. Adding an essay = adding a file,
  never editing a monolith. The URL slug comes from the filename.
- The assessment stays DATA-DRIVEN: trades, departments, and functions are data objects
  in src/components/Assessment.astro. To add a trade or question, add data — never
  hardcode UI per case.
- The assessment score is a DEPENDENCY score: higher = more depends on the owner = worse.
  Low is the good outcome. Keep this direction consistent everywhere.
- Keep the home page fast and uncluttered. The assessment loads as an overlay, not inline.

## Things NOT to do
- Don't add AI-generated stock imagery or fake screenshots.
- Don't add social-proof sections with invented numbers.
- Don't convert the publication into a conversion landing page "to improve conversion."
  It's a publication on purpose.
- Don't over-engineer: no CMS, no database, no auth. Markdown + static + one email
  integration is the whole system.
